transportation.name: metro
transportation.description: The Paris Metro is an efficient and cost-effective way to get around the city. It consists of 16 lines that cover most of the city, with trains running every few minutes.

transportation.name: buses
transportation.description: Paris has an extensive bus network that covers many areas of the city not served by the metro. Most buses run from around 6:00am to 8:30pm, with some lines operating 24 hours a day.

transportation.name: trains
transportation.description: The RER (Réseau Express Régional) is a regional train system that connects Paris to the surrounding suburbs. It is a fast and convenient way to travel to and from the city center.

transportation.name: taxis
transportation.description: Taxis are readily available throughout Paris, and can be hailed on the street or at designated taxi stands. Prices are regulated by the city, so you can expect to pay a set fare for your journey.

transportation.name: tram
transportation.description: The tram is another option for getting around Paris. It is a light rail system that operates in some areas of the city.

transportation.name: Noctilien night bus
transportation.description: The Noctilien night bus is a network of buses that operate in Paris between 12:30am and 5:30am, providing an alternative to the metro for late-night travel.

transportation.name: Vélib' public bike rental system
transportation.description: The Vélib' public bike rental system is a network of self-service bikes available for rent at various locations throughout Paris. It is a convenient and environmentally-friendly way to get around the city.
